1
00:00:01,516 --> 00:00:14,070
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-harto samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:16,053 --> 00:00:22,521
Majjhol Buddha, pienamente risvegliato.

3
00:00:22,542 --> 00:00:29,109
So, I'm going to talk about the extraordinary ability of the Buddha to teach.

4
00:00:30,236 --> 00:00:36,786
What I will talk about tonight are the extraordinary abilities that Buddha had to teach.

5
00:00:38,148 --> 00:00:45,758
So I have no doubt he was a very charismatic person, but that would not necessarily make him a good teacher.

6
00:00:47,060 --> 00:00:58,134
I have no doubt that he was an extraordinarily charismatic person, but this in itself would not have made him a particularly skilled teacher.

7
00:00:58,773 --> 00:01:17,929
So he had the ability to teach large groups, monastics, nuns and so on, lay people, and adapt his teaching to them.

8
00:01:19,612 --> 00:01:29,286
And he was especially acute when talking to individuals, catching their moods and opinions, and through various techniques was able to correct their views and practices.

9
00:01:31,510 --> 00:01:39,460
He was particularly skillful, he was particularly capable when he spoke to individuals, to individuals.

10
00:01:40,061 --> 00:01:44,828
He was able to capture their moods, their opinions.

11
00:01:45,296 --> 00:01:54,552
And thanks to different techniques, he was able to correct their opinions, their points of view and also their practice.

12
00:01:56,474 --> 00:01:57,918
Now, he wasn't always successful.

13
00:01:58,519 --> 00:02:02,084
A character called Dandapani went away clicking his tongue.

14
00:02:04,147 --> 00:02:06,210
It didn't always happen.

15
00:02:06,230 --> 00:02:10,478
A certain character called Dandapani

16
00:02:10,777 --> 00:02:19,651
he walked around shaking his tongue, that is, expressing his disapproval.

17
00:02:19,770 --> 00:02:32,169
So now the usual way he discussed subjects was to first listen fully to what the other was saying, then he would repeat back to them what they had just said to make sure they both understood.

18
00:02:32,188 --> 00:02:37,917
So the way he usually dealt with

19
00:02:38,081 --> 00:03:07,717
And he would correct the person by a Socratic method of questions and answers, yeah?

20
00:03:08,271 --> 00:03:17,099
After that, he corrected the person with a process of questions and answers of the Socratic type.

21
00:03:18,481 --> 00:03:35,798
Now, once the Buddha, once he'd expressed his position, he would then restate it again clearly and usually he would add a metaphor or an analogy, as he would say, because some people understand better that way.

22
00:03:36,604 --> 00:04:02,899
So, over the next few Buddha celebration days, I hope to take one technique after another.

23
00:04:05,512 --> 00:04:14,723
Nelle prossime giornate di celebrazioni del Buddha vorrei affrontare, trattare una tecnica dopo l'altra.

24
00:04:16,326 --> 00:04:18,649
And use a discourse to illustrate it.

25
00:04:20,831 --> 00:04:26,059
Utilizzando per illustrarla un discorso, uno dei sutta.

26
00:04:26,839 --> 00:04:30,625
So this is the shorter discourse with Malankya Putta.

27
00:04:32,156 --> 00:04:38,125
This, specifically, is the short speech with Malunchia Putta.

28
00:04:38,165 --> 00:04:51,562
It's an example of how he would guide intellectuals away from conceptual, speculative thinking, abstract and metaphysical ideas, and he'd guide them towards practical wisdom.

29
00:04:52,463 --> 00:04:54,665
And he wasn't shy to call them fools.

30
00:04:56,728 --> 00:05:01,995
This speech is an example of the way he

31
00:05:02,346 --> 00:05:24,358
guided and distanced people from an excessively conceptual and speculative way of thinking, by distancing them from too abstract and metaphysical ideas and instead by bringing them to a practical type of wisdom.

32
00:05:24,379 --> 00:05:27,442
And he had no fear of calling them fools when necessary.

33
00:05:28,839 --> 00:05:34,786
So Malunkhya Putta was the son of Malunkhya, who was married to an evaluator of the king of Kosala.

34
00:05:36,408 --> 00:05:46,860
And he became a Samana, a wandering ascetic.

35
00:05:47,382 --> 00:05:54,509
When he heard the Buddha speak, he took ordination under him, but he didn't attain liberation till he was very old.

36
00:05:56,312 --> 00:06:16,317
Divenne dunque un samana, una sceta errante, e quando ascoltò Udil Buddha parlare, prese l'abito sott'Udil con lui, però non ottenne la liberazione fino a quando non fu molto anziano.

37
00:06:18,221 --> 00:06:25,509
So now, while Malenkiaputta was alone meditating near Savatthi, in Jeta's grove and Arthapindika's monastery,

38
00:06:26,029 --> 00:06:29,934
he had been considering the subjects the Buddha would not answer.

39
00:06:29,973 --> 00:06:53,978
One day, while Malunkyaputta was alone and was meditating near Savatthi in the forest of Jeta, the monastery of Anathapindika, he was thinking about the topics to which the Buddha had not answered, the questions to which the Buddha had never given an answer.

40
00:06:55,307 --> 00:07:09,071
Now, these were the sort of metaphysical questions of the day, and he came to a decision that if the Buddha didn't give him satisfactory answers to his questions, he would lose confidence and leave the Sangha.

41
00:07:10,853 --> 00:07:22,091
It was about questions, questions that were raised, metaphysical questions of the time.

42
00:07:22,713 --> 00:07:38,194
And Malunkyaputta came to the decision that if Buddha had not given him satisfactory answers to these questions, he would have lost all faith in him and would have left the Sangha.

43
00:07:39,274 --> 00:07:45,322
So, in the late afternoon, Malunkyaputta came out of retreat and went to the Buddha.

44
00:07:45,783 --> 00:07:50,930
He bowed, sat down to one side, and told the Buddha of his thoughts.

45
00:07:52,074 --> 00:08:02,295
So, in the late afternoon, Manon Khyaputta left the retreat and went back to Buddha.

46
00:08:02,314 --> 00:08:10,692
She bowed, sat down on one side, sang a song, and expressed her thoughts to Buddha.

47
00:08:10,942 --> 00:08:16,932
Venerable Sir, while I was alone in meditation, the following thought arose in my mind.

48
00:08:17,533 --> 00:08:24,867
These speculative views have been left undeclared by the Blessed One, set aside and rejected by him.

49
00:08:25,226 --> 00:08:30,716
Namely, the world is eternal or the world is not eternal.

50
00:08:30,737 --> 00:08:33,422
The world is infinite or the world is finite.

51
00:08:33,789 --> 00:08:38,998
The soul is the same as the body or is the soul one thing and the body another?

52
00:08:39,599 --> 00:08:48,453
And after the death of the Tathāgata, that's the Buddha, does he exist or after death does he not exist?

53
00:08:49,054 --> 00:08:53,322
Or after death does the Tathāgata both exist and not exist?

54
00:08:53,721 --> 00:09:00,253
Or after death does the Tathāgata neither exist nor not exist?

55
00:09:02,748 --> 00:09:13,785
Venerable Lord, while I was meditating, the following thought came to my mind.

56
00:09:13,806 --> 00:09:20,397
These questions, these speculative questions, have been left unanswered by the Blessed One.

57
00:09:20,417 --> 00:09:23,643
They have been abandoned and rejected by Him.

58
00:09:23,663 --> 00:09:29,312
And they are as follows, namely, the world is eternal or the world is not eternal.

59
00:09:29,798 --> 00:09:34,283
The world is finished or the world is infinite.

60
00:09:34,303 --> 00:09:39,370
The soul is the same thing as the body, or the soul is one thing and the body is another.

61
00:09:39,390 --> 00:09:58,977
And then again, after death, after his death, the Tathagata continues to exist, Tathagata, the transcendent Buddha, or after death a Tathagata does not exist, or again after death a Tathagata exists and does not exist,

62
00:09:59,532 --> 00:10:05,139
o ancora dopo la morte un tatàgata non esiste né non esiste.

63
00:10:06,100 --> 00:10:13,830
Now, if the Blessed One knows, then let the Blessed One declare that to me, and I will lead the holy life under you.

64
00:10:15,192 --> 00:10:25,184
Se il Beato lo sa, allora che il Beato me lo dichiari apertamente, io condurrò la vita santa sotto la sua guida, sotto la tua guida.

65
00:10:26,227 --> 00:10:34,440
If the Blessed One does not know, then it is simple for one who does not know, does not see, to say, I do not know, I do not see.

66
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:38,245
Then I will abandon the training and return to the lay life.

67
00:10:40,269 --> 00:10:49,423
Se il beato non sa, allora è bene che colui che non sa e non vede dica ben chiaramente non so, non vedo.

68
00:10:49,442 --> 00:10:53,769
In questo caso abbandonerò l'addestramento e tornerò alla vita laica.

69
00:10:54,471 --> 00:10:54,530
Ah.

70
00:10:55,490 --> 00:11:09,042
Well now, Malunkiaputta, did I ever say to you, come Malunkiaputta, leave the holy life under me and I will declare to you whether I have answers to these questions or not?

71
00:11:09,062 --> 00:11:10,182
No, Venerable Sir.

72
00:11:11,985 --> 00:11:24,635
Well then, Malunkiaputta, have I ever told you, come Malunkiaputta, lead the holy life under my guidance and I will declare to you whether or not I have the answers to these questions?

73
00:11:25,493 --> 00:11:27,394
O Venerabile Signore.

74
00:11:27,414 --> 00:11:37,327
And did you ever say to me, Venerable Sir, I will lead the spiritual life under the Buddha only if the Buddha will declare these things to me?

75
00:11:38,408 --> 00:11:39,509
No, Venerable Sir.

76
00:11:41,452 --> 00:11:51,946
E mi hai mai detto, mi hai mai detto, Venerabile Signore, condurrò la vita spirituale sotto la guida del Buddha solo se il Buddha mi dichiarerà queste cose?

77
00:11:52,966 --> 00:11:54,589
O Venerabile Signore.

78
00:11:55,327 --> 00:12:08,697
So now the Buddha makes sure they both agree as to what has been said.

79
00:12:09,149 --> 00:12:19,078
So it seems to me that I did not say to you, come Malankya Buddha, lead the spiritual life under me and I will declare these things to you.

80
00:12:19,659 --> 00:12:28,229
And you never said to me, sir, I will lead the spiritual life under the Buddha only if the Buddha will declare these things to me.

81
00:12:28,269 --> 00:12:33,975
In which case, you foolish man, who are you and what are you rejecting?

82
00:12:35,726 --> 00:12:47,278
So, it seems that I did not tell you, come, malunkiaputta, lead the spiritual life under the guidance of Buddha and I will declare these things to you.

83
00:12:47,298 --> 00:12:56,488
And you never told me, Lord, I will lead the spiritual life under the guidance of Buddha, only if Buddha will declare these things to me.

84
00:12:56,508 --> 00:13:01,312
In this case, stupid man, who are you and what are you rejecting?

85
00:13:03,384 --> 00:13:18,383
Now, if anyone should say, I will not lead the holy life under the Blessed One until the Blessed One declares answers to these questions, they will still remain undeclared by the Tathagata and meanwhile the person would die.

86
00:13:18,423 --> 00:13:30,777
Ora, se qualcuno dicesse, non condurrò la vita santa sotto la guida del Buddha finché il Beato non avesse dichiarato le risposte a queste domande,

87
00:13:31,380 --> 00:13:39,472
These would remain undeclared by the Tathagata and in the meantime that person would die.

88
00:13:40,615 --> 00:13:51,149
Now the Buddha uses this usual technique to support what he's saying with an allegory or a metaphor.

89
00:13:51,169 --> 00:13:59,042
And now the Buddha uses, as usual, a technique that would serve as support

90
00:13:59,326 --> 00:14:04,475
to what he was saying, thus using a metaphor or allegory.

91
00:14:05,418 --> 00:14:17,351
Suppose, Malankyaputta, a man were wounded by an arrow thickly smeared with poison and his friends and companions, his kinsmen and relatives, brought a surgeon to treat him.

92
00:14:17,793 --> 00:14:34,091
And the man would say, I will not let the surgeon pull the arrow out until I know whether the man who wounded me was a noble, a brahmin, a merchant or a worker, whether he was tall or short or middle height, whether the bow was long or a crossbow.

93
00:14:34,426 --> 00:14:37,830
What kind of feathers the shaft that wounded me was fitted with?

94
00:14:38,570 --> 00:14:43,134
Whether those of a vulture, a heron, a hawk, a peacock, or a stork?

95
00:14:43,615 --> 00:14:56,249
And what kind of arrowhead it was that wounded me, whether it spiked, or razor-tipped, or curved, or barbed, or carved-toothed, or lancet-toothed?

96
00:14:56,328 --> 00:15:02,475
Oppone in Malunchia Putta che un uomo fosse ferito da una freccia densamente cosparsa di veleno.

97
00:15:02,860 --> 00:15:31,077
and that his friends and companions, relatives and colleagues, brought a surgeon to cure him, and that the man said, I will not allow the surgeon to extract this arrow until I know if the man who hurt me was a noble, a brahman, a merchant or a worker, if he was tall, short or of medium stature, if the bow was a long bow or a balustrade.

98
00:15:31,868 --> 00:15:35,813
What kind of feather was stuck in the arrow that hurt me?

99
00:15:35,833 --> 00:15:44,186
If the feathers of a fan, or of an iron, or of a falcon, or of a peacock, or of a cicada.

100
00:15:45,307 --> 00:15:47,630
And what kind of arrowhead did it hurt me?

101
00:15:47,691 --> 00:15:56,644
Sharp, with a razorhead tip, curved, crocheted, with veal teeth, or in the shape of a spear?

102
00:15:58,192 --> 00:16:02,836
All this would still be unknown to that man and meanwhile he would die.

103
00:16:02,897 --> 00:16:18,431
So too, Malonkhiputta, if anyone should say, I will not lead the holy life under the Blessed One until the Blessed One declares on these questions, they would still remain undeclared by the Tathagata and meanwhile that person would die.

104
00:16:18,451 --> 00:16:26,918
All this would not remain known to that man and meanwhile he would die.

105
00:16:27,471 --> 00:16:44,615
Allo stesso modo, ma l'unchia putta, se qualcuno dicesse, non condurrò la vita santa sotto il beato affinché il beato non si pronunci su tali questioni, queste rimarrebbero non dichiarate dal Tathagata e nel frattempo quella persona morirebbe.

106
00:16:45,255 --> 00:16:55,690
Now, the Buddha goes on to say that it's not true that the spiritual life cannot be led unless these speculative views are answered, and he reaffirms his position.

107
00:16:57,037 --> 00:17:11,473
Then Buddha continues by saying that it is not true that spiritual life cannot be conducted without such speculative questions finding an answer, and reaffirms his position.

108
00:17:13,276 --> 00:17:25,170
Whether such views are answered or not, there is still birth, there is still aging, there is still death, there is still sorrow, lamentation, pain, grief and despair.

109
00:17:25,807 --> 00:17:31,494
And it is the destruction of these, right here and now, that I prescribe for.

110
00:17:33,117 --> 00:17:42,410
That such questions find less answer, there is always birth, there is always aging, there is always death.

111
00:17:43,151 --> 00:17:49,699
There is always pain, lament, sadness, affliction and despair.

112
00:17:49,719 --> 00:17:55,646
And it is the destruction of these things, right here and now, that I prescribe.

113
00:17:56,538 --> 00:18:06,076
Therefore, Malunkya Putta, remember what I have left undeclared as undeclared, and remember what I have declared as declared.

114
00:18:06,115 --> 00:18:18,259
Pertanto, Malunkya Putta, ricorda ciò che ho lasciato non dichiarato come non dichiarato, e ricorda ciò che ho dichiarato come dichiarato.

115
00:18:19,555 --> 00:18:21,497
And why have I left them undeclared?

116
00:18:21,717 --> 00:18:23,239
Because they are not beneficial.

117
00:18:23,659 --> 00:18:27,262
They do not belong to the fundamentals of the spiritual life.

118
00:18:27,282 --> 00:18:35,451
They do not lead to disenchantment, to dispassion, to cessation, to peace, to direct knowledge, to awakening, to nibbana.

119
00:18:36,271 --> 00:18:38,634
That is why I have left them undeclared.

120
00:18:40,556 --> 00:18:42,518
And why have I left them undeclared?

121
00:18:43,138 --> 00:18:49,005
Because they are not beneficial, they do not belong to the foundations of the holy and spiritual life.

122
00:18:49,458 --> 00:19:00,583
non conducono al disincanto, al distacco, alla cessazione, alla pace, alla conoscenza diretta, al risveglio, al nibbana.

123
00:19:00,603 --> 00:19:03,388
Ecco perché li ho lasciati non dichiarati.

124
00:19:04,432 --> 00:19:06,015
And what have I declared?

125
00:19:06,333 --> 00:19:08,915
There is suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

126
00:19:09,195 --> 00:19:12,200
There is the origin of suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

127
00:19:12,660 --> 00:19:22,471
There is a cessation of suffering and unsatisfactoriness and there is a way leading to the cessation of suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

128
00:19:23,913 --> 00:19:26,336
E cosa ho dichiarato?

129
00:19:26,355 --> 00:19:29,740
C'è sofferenza e insoddisfazione.

130
00:19:29,759 --> 00:19:33,723
C'è l'origine della sofferenza e dell'insoddisfazione.

131
00:19:34,210 --> 00:19:46,190
c'è la cessazione della sofferenza e dell'insoddisfazione, e c'è la via che conduce alla cessazione della sofferenza e dell'insoddisfazione.

132
00:19:46,230 --> 00:19:55,005
That is what the Blessed One said, and the Venerable Malamkhya Buddha was satisfied and delighted in the Blessed One's words.

133
00:19:56,227 --> 00:19:58,210
Questo è ciò che disse il Beato.

134
00:19:58,492 --> 00:20:05,740
The Venerable Manu Khyaputta was satisfied and delighted by the words of the Blessed One.

135
00:20:05,760 --> 00:20:15,131
So this discourse shows us how the Buddha generally taught by first listening and then probing and then finally stating his teachings and his use of metaphor.

136
00:20:16,593 --> 00:20:25,782
This discourse shows how in general Buddha taught first by listening, then

137
00:20:26,017 --> 00:20:32,887
and then finally affirming his teaching and finally the use of the metaphor.

138
00:20:34,009 --> 00:20:48,835
And he would not be drawn into hypothetical, metaphysical or speculative discussions.

139
00:20:49,894 --> 00:21:06,680
They were simply not conducive to the spiritual aim of liberating oneself from dukkha, suffering and unsatisfactoriness.

140
00:21:11,247 --> 00:21:14,251
The Buddha tells us there is a limit beyond reason.

141
00:21:14,311 --> 00:21:17,876
Reason and logic simply cannot go.

142
00:21:18,228 --> 00:21:22,555
and which can only be transcended and realized by direct experience.

143
00:21:24,397 --> 00:21:39,641
Il Buddha ci dice che c'è un limite oltre il quale ragione e logica non possono andare e che può essere trasceso soltanto e realizzato solamente grazie a una esperienza diretta.

144
00:21:40,362 --> 00:21:44,808
And finally, the reason he refused to answer questions about himself

145
00:21:45,295 --> 00:22:00,647
What happened to him after he died was that these questions invariably arose from some idea of a self that would either exist or not exist, exist and not exist, and neither exist nor not exist.

146
00:22:02,349 --> 00:22:13,799
And finally, the reason why he refused to answer these questions about himself, the Tathagata, that is, what would have happened after his death,

147
00:22:14,404 --> 00:22:34,064
was that this type of questions arose invariably from some idea of a if that would have existed or not existed, or has existed and not existed, or has existed or not existed.

148
00:22:35,945 --> 00:22:36,465
Very good.

149
00:22:36,526 --> 00:22:42,251
I hope this little talk has been of some assistance, that it has not caused confusion.

150
00:22:44,375 --> 00:22:50,662
Spero che questo piccolo sermone sia stato di aiuto e che non abbia creato confusione alcuna.

151
00:22:51,102 --> 00:22:59,651
That by your careful practice and reading you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

152
00:22:59,671 --> 00:23:11,344
E che grazie alla vostra pratica, alla lettura dei discorsi, sarete liberati dalla sofferenza sperabilmente prima piuttosto che dopo.

